FILL_CH15 = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 15 addresses the most intellectually contested issue between Paul and the Corinthian community: the resurrection of the body. The chapter opens with the gospel Paul preached and they received — a reminder that the resurrection proclamation was not a later theological addition but the foundational content of the initial mission. The Corinthians' problem is not with the past event (Jesus's resurrection) but with the future event (believers' resurrection) — a distinction Paul will spend the entire chapter collapsing.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Paul's concern that the Corinthians 'believed in vain' (<em>eikē episteuatte</em>) situates the resurrection within the category of essential gospel content, not peripheral doctrine. In ancient epistolary rhetoric, the <em>narratio</em> (statement of fact) typically preceded the <em>probatio</em> (argument); Paul here states the tradition (vv. 1-11) before arguing from it (vv. 12-58). The 'holding fast' (<em>katechete</em>) language echoes Passover holding-fast language in Exodus — the tradition that saves must be gripped and retained.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The creedal formula (vv. 3-5) is widely recognized as the earliest fixed theological tradition in the NT, likely originating within 5 years of the crucifixion. Paul's 'received... delivered' (<em>parelabon... paredōka</em>) uses the technical Jewish tradition-transmission vocabulary (<em>qibbel... masar</em>), indicating this was a formally transmitted deposit, not Paul's own theological construction. The formula's four-element structure (died / buried / raised / appeared) is parallel and balanced, suggesting liturgical use in the earliest communities.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'He was buried' — the burial specification in the creedal formula is not incidental but addresses the potential objection that the resurrection appearances were visions of a spiritual entity rather than a bodily resurrection. The burial establishes the physical reality of death: whatever rose on the third day is what was laid in the tomb. The 'third day' (<em>tē hēmera tē tritē</em>) may reflect the Jewish interpretive tradition that God does not leave the righteous in Sheol beyond three days (cf. Ps 16:10 LXX; Jonah 1:17; Hos 6:2).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Cephas (Peter) as the first named resurrection witness reflects the tradition preserved in Luke 24:34 ('The Lord has risen and has appeared to Simon'). Peter's primacy in the appearance sequence is consistent across all four Gospels (Mark 16:7; Matt 28:7; Luke 24:12, 34; John 20:1-10; 21). The appearance 'to the Twelve' reflects the reconstituted apostolic circle (even after Judas's betrayal and before Matthias's appointment — the twelve here is a title, not a precise headcount).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The appearance to 'more than five hundred brothers at one time' is not recorded in the canonical Gospels and represents an independent tradition preserved in the Pauline corpus. Paul's note that 'most of them are still alive' (<em>hoi pleiones menousin heōs arti</em>) at the time of writing (~53-54 CE) is a forensic argument: the witnesses are available for consultation. This is the kind of claim that would be falsifiable by investigation — Paul would not make it if the witnesses could not corroborate it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The appearance to James (the Lord's brother) fills an important gap: James was apparently not a follower during Jesus's ministry (John 7:5) but became the leader of the Jerusalem church (Acts 15:13; Gal 1:19; 2:9). The resurrection appearance to James is the only plausible explanation for his transformation from skeptic to leader of the Jerusalem community. Paul's listing of James separately from 'the apostles' suggests a distinct appearance tradition with its own provenance.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Paul's self-description as 'one untimely born' (<em>ektroma</em>) — an aborted fetus, or a premature/miscarried birth — uses a startling image for his place in the apostolic sequence. The term conveys both abnormality (he did not witness the earthly ministry) and violent discontinuity (his apostolic birth was through a traumatic encounter rather than the normal developmental process). The Damascus road experience was Paul's resurrection appearance — later than the others, unexpected, and preceded by his persecution of the community.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The self-description as 'the least of the apostles' (<em>ho elachistos ton apostolōn</em>) and 'unfit to be called an apostle' reflects Paul's awareness of his status in the apostolic community. His persecution of 'the church of God' was a concrete historical fact that opponents used against him (Gal 1:13; Acts 8:3; 9:1-2). The contrast between his past violence and his present apostolic labor grounds the argument about grace (v. 10) in biographical reality rather than abstract humility.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The 'grace of God' (<em>charis tou Theou</em>) that made Paul what he is — and 'was not in vain' — echoes the earlier warning about the Corinthians' believing 'in vain' (v. 2). Paul's labor (<em>ekopiasa</em>, I worked hard) reflects his actual apostolic activity: founding churches across Asia Minor, Macedonia, Greece. The paradox of divine grace and human effort — 'it was not I but the grace of God that is with me' — is a characteristically Pauline resolution of the problem of human agency under divine sovereignty.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The unity of apostolic proclamation ('whether I or they, so we preach and so you believed') establishes that the resurrection tradition was not Paul's idiosyncratic teaching but the common content of all apostolic preaching. This is important for the argument that follows: the Corinthians' resurrection-denial is not a dispute with Paul's peculiar theology but a rejection of the universal apostolic tradition. The witnesses' consensus is the evidential base for what Paul is about to argue.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The logical structure of Paul's argument (vv. 13-19) uses a series of conditionals (<em>ei de</em>, 'but if') to expose the consequences of resurrection-denial. If there is no resurrection of the dead, then Christ has not been raised — and the entire structure of the apostolic proclamation collapses. This is a reductio ad absurdum argument familiar in Greco-Roman rhetoric: the Corinthian position, when followed to its logical conclusion, destroys the very Christian identity the Corinthians claim to hold.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Paul's claim that his preaching would be empty (<em>kenon</em>) and the Corinthians' faith empty without the resurrection reflects the resurrection's constitutive role in early Christianity. This distinguishes the Christian movement from Stoic or Platonic philosophical communities: membership in those communities did not depend on the truth of a specific historical event. The historical particularity of the resurrection — a specific person raised at a specific time — is the kind of contingent claim that philosophical religions typically avoided. Paul insists on it as non-negotiable.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The characterization of the apostles as 'false witnesses of God' (<em>pseudomartyres tou Theou</em>) if Christ is not raised sharpens the stakes. <em>Martyria</em> (testimony/witness) was a legal category in ancient courts: a false witness was subject to the penalty that would have applied to the accused (Deut 19:18-19). The apostolic witness to the resurrection is a public juridical claim that, if false, makes the apostles perjurers before the divine court. Paul is not allowing the resurrection to be quietly demythologized into a spiritual truth; it is a claim about what God actually did in history.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The parallel repetition of the conditional (v. 16 repeating v. 13) is a rhetorical device of emphasis: the argument bears repeating because the stakes are so high. In ancient persuasion theory (<em>enargia</em>), vivid and repeated statement of consequences was used to help the audience feel the force of an argument. Paul's repetition is not careless but deliberate: if the foundation (Christ's resurrection) fails, everything built on it (faith, forgiveness, hope) falls simultaneously.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Your faith is futile and you are still in your sins' — the soteriological consequence of resurrection-denial is the most radical in the chain: forgiveness of sins is tied to the resurrection. In early Christian proclamation (Acts 2:38; 10:43; 13:38), forgiveness was specifically connected to the risen Christ's authority and the Spirit's gift following the resurrection. A dead Christ who remains dead cannot forgive sin because the verdict of the cross (condemned as a criminal) has not been reversed by the divine act of resurrection.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Those who have 'fallen asleep' (<em>koimēthentes</em>) in Christ — deceased believers — face the bleakest consequence if resurrection is false: they have 'perished' (<em>apōlonto</em>). The Corinthian overrealized eschatology ('we are already spiritually resurrected') may have contributed to the community's casual attitude toward members who had died — perhaps the 'baptism for the dead' (v. 29) reflects community concern for deceased members Paul can leverage for his argument.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'If in this life only we have hoped in Christ, we are of all people most to be pitied' — the social reality of the early Christian community makes this poignant. Early Christians faced social stigma, economic marginalization, periodic persecution, and the suspicion of Roman authorities. If the resurrection is false, the entire cost of Christian community membership (social disruption, family tension, potential legal jeopardy) has been paid for nothing. The pre-Pauline tradition already knew the eschatological consolation that made suffering worthwhile was the resurrection hope.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The pivot to confidence: Christ has been raised as the firstfruits (<em>aparchē</em>) of those who sleep. The agricultural metaphor of firstfruits was deeply embedded in Israel's festival calendar: the first portion of the grain harvest offered to God at Pentecost consecrated and guaranteed the whole harvest (Lev 23:9-14). Paul uses this agricultural-liturgical concept to argue that Christ's resurrection is not an isolated event but the beginning of a harvest — the general resurrection of the dead is as certain as the main harvest following the firstfruits.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Adam-Christ typology introduced here has deep roots in Second Temple Jewish reflection on Genesis 1-3. The figure of Adam as the representative human whose sin brought universal death was developed in 4 Ezra (3:7; 7:11-12) and 2 Baruch (17:3; 23:4; 54:15), where Adam's transgression is the origin of universal mortality. Paul's typological reading makes the first Adam and the last Adam parallel representative figures whose actions determine the fate of all who are 'in' them — either death or resurrection life.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'As in Adam all die, so in Christ all will be made alive' — the 'all' (<em>pantes</em>) in both halves has generated debate about universalism (will literally all people ultimately be raised to life?). In context, Paul's 'all' in the second clause is qualified by 'those who belong to Christ' (v. 23). The parallel structure is typological and representative, not arithmetically universal: Adam's act had consequences for all who are 'in Adam' (i.e., all humanity through natural descent); Christ's resurrection has consequences for all who are 'in Christ' (i.e., all who belong to the new humanity through faith).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The ordering — Christ the firstfruits, then those who belong to Christ at his parousia (<em>en tē parousia autou</em>) — introduces the eschatological timetable. <em>Parousia</em> (arrival, presence, visit) was a technical term for the official visit of a king or emperor to a city, with associated public ceremonies and demonstrations of honor. Paul's use of <em>parousia</em> for Christ's return frames the resurrection event within a royal-arrival framework: the returning king vindicates his people and establishes his reign.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The 'end' (<em>telos</em>) when Christ delivers the kingdom to God the Father describes an eschatological sequence found in Jewish apocalyptic literature (4 Ezra 7:28-29; 2 Baruch 40:3). The destruction of 'every rule, authority, and power' reflects the Second Temple Jewish tradition that heavenly powers (angelic rulers, cosmic forces) were enemies of God's people that the Messiah would ultimately defeat (1 Enoch 90:19-25; 4Q285). Paul adapts this tradition to describe the comprehensive cosmic victory that Christ's reign accomplishes.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The citation of Psalm 110:1 ('he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet') was one of the most important proof-texts in early Christianity. Psalm 110 was the most-cited OT passage in the NT, and its interpretation as messianic had Second Temple precedent (though its application to Jesus was distinctively Christian). The 'until' (<em>achri hou</em>) frames the current age: Christ is already reigning (post-resurrection/ascension) but the full subjection of all enemies is still in process.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'The last enemy to be destroyed is death' — this statement places death within the category of cosmic powers (<em>arche</em>, <em>exousia</em>, <em>dynamis</em>) that Christ's reign conquers. In Second Temple Jewish apocalyptic, Death was often personified as a cosmic power or angelic figure (1 Enoch 21; 4 Ezra 8:53-54). Paul's claim that death is the <em>last</em> enemy frames the entire interim period (between resurrection and parousia) as a campaign of progressive conquest, with the final battle being the destruction of death itself at the general resurrection.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The citation of Psalm 8:6 ('he has put all things under his feet') interprets the psalm messianically — originally about the honor given to 'humanity' (<em>ben adam</em>), Paul reads it as fulfilled in the Last Adam, the risen Christ. This messianic reading of Psalm 8 is found elsewhere in the NT (Eph 1:22; Heb 2:6-8) and may represent an early Christian exegetical tradition. The exception clause ('obviously not including the one who subjected all things to him') prevents a reading where the Son is equal to the Father in this subjection process.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The ultimate subjection of the Son to the Father ('that God may be all in all') has generated extensive theological debate about the eternal relationship of Father and Son. The eschatological framing is crucial: Paul is describing the <em>telos</em> (end, completion) of the redemptive drama, not making a permanent ontological statement about the Son's subordination. The formula 'God all in all' (<em>theos panta en pasin</em>) is close to Jewish expressions of divine completeness and comprehensiveness (cf. Sir 43:27; Philo, On Flight 112).</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Why do we face danger every hour?' — Paul's argument from the apostles' lifestyle is an ad hominem argument from pragmatics: if there is no resurrection, the apostolic missionary life is simply irrational. The catalog of dangers Paul faced (2 Cor 11:23-27: beatings, imprisonments, stoning, shipwrecks) was a social reality known to the Corinthians. An Epicurean would say such a life was foolish; Paul's counter is that the resurrection hope makes it rational. The argument from apostolic praxis was a form of evidence for the truth of the proclamation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'I die every day' — the metaphorical dying-daily of apostolic risk-taking. The boasting 'by your pride in you' (<em>tē hymetera kauchēsei hēn echō en Christō Iēsou</em>) grounds the claim in the apostle-community relationship: the Corinthian community is the living evidence of Paul's apostolic labor that he is willing to risk daily. In ancient philosophical traditions, the wise man was said to 'practice dying' (Socrates in Plato's Phaedo 67e; Seneca, Letters 26.8) — Paul makes the same claim but for practical missionary service, not philosophical detachment.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'What do I gain if, humanly speaking, I fought with beasts at Ephesus?' — whether Paul literally faced animal combat in the arena (which would likely have killed him) or uses the metaphor for severe human opposition at Ephesus (cf. 2 Cor 1:8-10: 'we despaired of life itself') is debated. Roman citizens like Paul had legal protection from capital punishment in arena combat; the metaphorical reading fits better. The citation of Isa 22:13 ('let us eat and drink, for tomorrow we die') is an Epicurean-adjacent slogan that Paul quotes to represent the logical implication of resurrection denial: hedonism is rational if death is final.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Do not be deceived: bad company ruins good morals' (<em>phtheirousin ēthē chrēsth' homiliai kakai</em>) is a citation from the Greek comic playwright Menander (Thais, fragment 218) — the only direct citation of secular Greek literature in the undisputed Pauline letters. That Paul cites a comic playwright shows his rhetorical education and his willingness to use culturally resonant sources. The proverb was apparently proverbial by Paul's time; his use of it addresses the social reality that the Corinthians' association with resurrection-deniers was corrupting the community's moral formation.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Come to your senses as you ought and stop sinning' (<em>ekneepsate dikaiōs kai mē hamartanete</em>) — the sobriety metaphor (<em>ekneipsate</em> = sober up from drunkenness) was used in Stoic and Platonic philosophy for the return to rational clarity after passion or error. The 'some among you have no knowledge of God' (<em>agnosian Theou tines echousin</em>) is pointed: in a community that prided itself on <em>gnōsis</em> (knowledge), some members are characterized as manifesting divine ignorance in their resurrection-denial. The shame appeal ('I say this to your shame') deliberately invokes Corinthian honor-competition.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The interlocutor's question ('How are the dead raised? With what kind of body do they come?') represents the standard Greco-Roman philosophical objection to bodily resurrection. For Platonic and Stoic thinkers, the body was the soul's encumbrance or material vehicle — its reconstitution after dissolution was both physically unintelligible and philosophically undesirable. The objection was stock enough to be addressed in 2 Maccabees 7:10-11 (the third martyred brother holds out his hands saying 'these I received from Heaven and for his sake I disregard them and from him I hope to receive them back') — the Jewish martyrdom tradition had already developed responses to the question.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Paul's dismissal of the interlocutor as 'foolish' (<em>aphron</em>) is rhetorically aggressive — the normal form of the diatribe rhetorical device (<em>diatribē</em>, imagined dispute with an opponent) in Greek philosophical discussion. The seed-and-plant analogy that follows was already used in Jewish reflection on resurrection: 4 Ezra 4:30-32 compares the resurrection to a grain of wheat sown in the ground. Paul deploys this widely-known agricultural analogy to argue that transformation-through-death is a natural, observable process that undermines the 'with what body?' objection.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The distinction between the seed sown and the body that will be — 'perhaps wheat or some other grain' — grounds the botanical analogy in observable agricultural fact known to the Corinthians. Corinth's territory included farmland (the Corinthian plain north of the city); the seed-harvest cycle was a universal experiential reference point. The discontinuity-within-continuity of seed → plant is Paul's primary model for the resurrection body's relationship to the present body: the same organism, transformed beyond recognition.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'God gives it a body as he has chosen' — the theological claim behind the botanical analogy is divine creative sovereignty. The variety of bodies in creation (vv. 39-41: humans, animals, birds, fish; terrestrial vs. celestial bodies) argues that God is not limited to one type of body-form but creates appropriate bodies for different conditions. The resurrection body will be the kind of body appropriate to the conditions of the coming age — just as the mature plant is the body appropriate to the sunlit condition, as opposed to the seed's dormant underground condition.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The four-fold division of flesh types — human, animal, bird, fish — reflects ancient natural philosophy. Aristotle's Historia Animalium organized the animal kingdom into similar categories. Paul uses the diversity of physical forms (all different kinds of 'flesh' — <em>sarx</em>) to argue that there is no single template for a 'body'; the assumption that a resurrection body must look like the present body is as naive as assuming a plant must look like the seed. Divine creativity in physical form is the premise of the resurrection body argument.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The contrast between celestial (<em>epourania</em>) and terrestrial (<em>epigeia</em>) bodies extends the diversity argument to the astronomical domain. In Greco-Roman natural philosophy, the heavenly bodies (sun, moon, stars, planets) were composed of a fifth element (<em>quintessence</em>) or <em>aithēr</em> (luminous fire) distinct from the four earthly elements. Paul uses this two-realm cosmology to argue that the resurrection body will be as different from the present body as celestial matter is from terrestrial matter — glorious, luminous, appropriate to its cosmic environment.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The differential glory of sun, moon, and stars was an observable astronomical fact known to every ancient person. The stars' varying brightness (some are brighter than others) was noted by Greek astronomers (Hipparchus's star catalog, 2nd cent. BCE, classified stars by magnitude). Paul's point is that 'glory' (<em>doxa</em>) is not uniform even in the heavenly realm; the resurrection bodies of the dead may similarly have differential characteristics. The use of astronomical knowledge to argue for resurrection body glory was a distinctively Jewish-Christian rhetorical move.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The four antitheses (vv. 42-44) — perishable/imperishable, dishonor/glory, weakness/power, natural/spiritual — are the rhetorical climax of the resurrection-body argument. Each antithesis names what the present body is (the 'what is sown' side) and what the resurrection body will be. <em>Atimia</em> (dishonor) for the buried body reflects the cultural shame of death and burial in the ancient world — corpse-handling made one ritually impure in both Jewish (Num 19:11-13) and some Gentile contexts. The resurrection body's 'glory' reverses this shame.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The 'weakness' (<em>astheneia</em>) of the buried body refers to its incapacity and physical failure at death. The vocabulary of 'power' (<em>dynamis</em>) for the resurrection body recalls the 'power of God' language applied to the cross (1:18) — the same divine power that raised Christ reverses the weakness of death. In Hellenistic royal ideology, the emperor displayed <em>dynamis</em> through military conquest and public building projects; Paul reconfigures power as the eschatological reversal of bodily weakness, not imperial domination.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The 'natural body' (<em>sōma psychikon</em>) and 'spiritual body' (<em>sōma pneumatikon</em>) are categories derived from Paul's <em>psychē/pneuma</em> anthropology. <em>Psychikon</em> = soul-driven, animated by the <em>psychē</em> (the ordinary human animating principle). <em>Pneumatikon</em> = Spirit-driven, animated by the divine <em>pneuma</em>. The contrast is not between material and immaterial bodies but between the present body animated by ordinary human life-force and the resurrection body animated by the eschatological Spirit — still a body, but a transformed, Spirit-pervaded one.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The citation of Gen 2:7 ('the first Adam became a living being') and its expansion ('the last Adam became a life-giving spirit') is a midrashic interpretation of the creation account. In Second Temple Judaism, Adam was seen as both a historical figure and a cosmic/representative type (Philo, On the Creation 134-148; Wisdom of Solomon 10:1-2). The 'last Adam' interpretation — applying the Genesis text typologically to Christ — is Paul's own theological innovation, though built on existing Adam-speculation in the Jewish tradition.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The insistence that 'the spiritual was not first but the natural' counters the Platonic ordering (in Philo, the heavenly Adam of Gen 1:26-27 preceded the earthly Adam of Gen 2:7 — the heavenly form is the ideal). Paul reverses this: the earthly, historical, natural order (Adam) came first; the spiritual, eschatological order (Christ) comes second. This temporal ordering argues that resurrection-glory is not the recovery of a pre-fallen spiritual state but the advance into an eschatological new creation that exceeds even Eden.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The 'man of dust' (<em>choikos</em>) echoes Gen 2:7's creation from <em>adamah</em> (ground/earth): Adam's name itself encodes his earthy origin. The 'man of heaven' (<em>ouranios</em>) is the risen and ascended Christ in his glorified state. This vertical contrast (earth/heaven) maps onto the temporal contrast (first/last Adam) and the two-age contrast (present age/coming age). Paul uses the Jewish Adam-speculation tradition to argue that the resurrection body will be as appropriate to the coming age as the earthy body is to the present age.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The collective argument: 'as was the man of dust, so also are those who are of the dust; and as is the man of heaven, so also are those who are of heaven.' The two representative figures determine the nature of those who belong to them — Adam's people share his earthy nature; Christ's people will share his heavenly nature at the resurrection. This solidarity-through-representation is the Pauline logic of corporate identity: identity is determined by the representative figure one belongs to.</p>",
    "49": "<p>'Just as we have borne the image of the man of dust, we shall also bear the image of the man of heaven' — the image (<em>eikōn</em>) vocabulary echoes Gen 1:26-27's 'image of God' (<em>tselem Elohim</em>). The tradition that humanity bears God's image, distorted by the fall, was central to Second Temple Jewish anthropology (Wisdom 2:23; Sirach 17:1-4; 2 Baruch 54:21). Paul's resurrection-body theology is simultaneously a restoration and surpassing of the original creation: the resurrection image exceeds the Adamic image as the eschatological surpasses the protological.</p>",
    "50": "<p>'Flesh and blood cannot inherit the kingdom of God' — this statement is the hinge between the resurrection-body argument (vv. 35-49) and the transformation-of-the-living section (vv. 51-57). The phrase 'flesh and blood' (<em>sarx kai haima</em>) is a Jewish idiom for mortal humanity in its weakness (cf. Matt 16:17; Gal 1:16; Eph 6:12; Sir 14:18). The prohibition is not that matter cannot enter the kingdom but that perishable mortal flesh cannot — transformation, not liberation from body, is the requirement.</p>",
    "51": "<p>Paul announces a 'mystery' (<em>mystērion</em>) — a revealed divine secret, as in the Jewish apocalyptic tradition where heavenly mysteries are disclosed to seers (1 Enoch 41:1; 4 Ezra 14:5-6; Daniel 2:28). The specific mystery: 'we will not all sleep, but we will all be changed.' The expectation that some of the current community would survive until the parousia reflects the early Christian eschatological timetable. Paul's pastoral concern is for both the living and the dead: all will be transformed, none excluded from the resurrection event.</p>",
    "52": "<p>The instantaneous transformation — 'in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, at the last trumpet' — draws on Jewish apocalyptic imagery of the final trumpet as the signal for resurrection and judgment. The trumpet-at-the-end tradition appears in Isaiah 27:13 (the great trumpet summons the scattered), Zephaniah 1:14-16, Zechariah 9:14, and the Synoptic apocalypse (Matt 24:31). The Qumran War Scroll (1QM) depicts the final eschatological battle with elaborate trumpet signals. Paul uses this tradition to frame the resurrection as a cosmic event with a clear signal.</p>",
    "53": "<p>'This perishable body must put on the imperishable, and this mortal body must put on immortality' — the clothing metaphor for the resurrection transformation was common in ancient Jewish and Hellenistic discourse. The heavenly 'garments of glory' appear in Second Temple texts (1 Enoch 62:15-16; 2 Enoch 22:8-10; T. Levi 8:2). Paul's use of the clothing metaphor emphasizes continuity (the same 'I' who is perishable puts on imperishability) while conveying transformation (the new garment transforms the wearer's condition).</p>",
    "54": "<p>The conflation of Isaiah 25:8 ('he will swallow up death forever') and Hosea 13:14 ('where, O death, are your plagues?') as a combined proof-text was standard Jewish pesher exegesis — linking texts by common vocabulary and subject matter. Isaiah 25:8 was interpreted in the Targum as referring to the eschatological resurrection; Hosea 13:14 in the MT is ambiguous (possibly a threat against Israel), but Paul reads it with the LXX in a redemptive direction. The combination of two prophetic texts amplifies the resurrection-victory claim.</p>",
    "55": "<p>The victory-taunt over death — 'where, O death, is your victory? where, O death, is your sting?' — is a rhetorical apostrophe (direct address to an absent or abstract figure). The Stoic tradition included 'philosophical taunts' over death as a way of demonstrating the sage's fearlessness (Seneca, Letters 77.19). Paul's taunt is not Stoic detachment (death doesn't matter) but eschatological triumph (death has been defeated). The corporate dimension is crucial: this is not the private philosopher's equanimity but the community's shared eschatological confession.</p>",
    "56": "<p>'The sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the law' — a compressed theological statement that connects soteriology and resurrection. Death's power to destroy depends on sin's reality; sin's power to condemn depends on the law's authority to count it against us. The resurrection of Christ (and of believers) defeats all three in sequence: resurrection overcomes death, which removes sin's lethal power, which removes the law's condemning function. The sequence is the soteriological logic of Romans 5-8 compressed into one sentence.</p>",
    "57": "<p>'Thanks be to God, who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ' — the doxological conclusion to the resurrection argument. In Jewish benediction form (<em>berakah</em>), the acknowledgment of God as the giver of salvation typically followed the rehearsal of saving acts. Paul's doxology frames the entire resurrection chapter as an act of theological worship: the argument is not academic but devotional — the resurrection is the ground of gratitude and praise, not merely of intellectual assent.</p>",
    "58": "<p>The practical conclusion — 'be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the Lord's work, knowing that your labor is not in vain' — grounds the ethical application in the resurrection. In Stoic ethics, the good action was its own reward and the philosophical sage acted without regard to consequences. Paul's opposite: the resurrection makes the consequences of present action determinative — labor now is not lost but gathered into the eschatological harvest. The 'not in vain' (<em>ouk estin kenōs</em>) directly counters the 'vain' faith of v. 2 and the 'vain' preaching of v. 14: resurrection validates both the apostolic mission and the community's life of obedience.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH16 = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The collection for the Jerusalem saints (<em>hē logia</em> — a technical term for a religious collection or voluntary contribution) was a major project occupying Paul across multiple letters (1 Cor 16:1-4; 2 Cor 8-9; Gal 2:10; Rom 15:25-27). The collection had multiple dimensions: practical relief for a poor community (the Jerusalem church suffered from both poverty and periodic famine), theological significance as a Gentile act of solidarity with the Jewish mother-church, and possibly an eschatological dimension as the 'pilgrimage of the nations' bringing tribute to Zion (Isa 2:2-4; 60:5-7). The Galatian churches also participated, suggesting a geographically broad campaign.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The 'first day of the week' (<em>kata mian sabbatou</em>) Sunday deposit is one of the earliest references to Sunday as the primary Christian gathering day. The shift from the Sabbath (seventh day) to the first day is attested by multiple early Christian sources (Ignatius, To the Magnesians 9.1; Didache 14.1; Justin Martyr, First Apology 67) and reflects the resurrection-first-day tradition (all four Gospels place the resurrection on the first day). Paul's instruction creates a weekly saving discipline: each Sunday gathering, members set aside a portion — avoiding a large last-minute collection that might be a burden.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The plan to send approved representatives with letters of accreditation to carry the collection to Jerusalem reflects the ancient practice of formal delegation for financial transfers. The Roman world had developed sophisticated mechanisms for transferring value across distances, including letters of credit (<em>litterae</em>) carried by trusted messengers. Paul's concern that the collection be handled by community-designated and accredited representatives was also a form of financial accountability: the apostle was not enriching himself from the collection (2 Cor 8:20-21 shows this was a live concern).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Paul's flexibility about accompanying the delegation reflects his contingency planning. The final decision (Rom 15:25-28, written after 1 Corinthians) was to accompany the collection personally to Jerusalem — a decision with profound consequences (it led to his arrest, Acts 21:27-36). The phrase 'if it seems worthwhile for me to go also' suggests Paul was weighing the political and missional dynamics: a personal apostolic presentation of the collection would maximize its symbolic impact but exposed him to the Jerusalem community tensions he navigated carefully (Gal 2:1-10).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Paul's travel plan — through Macedonia before coming to Corinth — explains the delay between this letter and his arrival. The Macedonian churches (Philippi, Thessalonica, Beroea) were also participating in the collection and required a pastoral visit. Paul's travel through Macedonia is reflected in Acts 20:1-6. The planned extended stay in Corinth ('spending the winter with you') reflects the ancient winter travel restrictions: Mediterranean sea travel was considered dangerous from November through March, and overland winter travel was slower. Paul intended to wait out the sailing season in Corinth.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The 'sending on' (<em>propempthō</em>) language was a technical term for a community's formal support of a traveler with provisions, companions, and letters of introduction. The Corinthians were expected to equip Paul for whatever journey followed his winter stay — whether to Jerusalem with the collection or further west toward Spain (Rom 15:24, 28). The term reflects the patron-client dynamics of ancient travel: communities supported traveling missionaries and apostles as acts of partnership in the mission.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Paul's desire to spend 'some time' rather than a brief passing visit reflects the depth of the Corinthian pastoral situation. The letter itself is evidence of multiple complex problems requiring sustained engagement. The qualification 'if the Lord permits' (<em>ean ho kyrios epitrepsē</em>) reflects the eschatological contingency of all planning (cf. Jas 4:15) and Paul's awareness that his travel plans were subject to divine redirection (cf. Acts 16:6-10; Rom 1:13).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Paul's plan to stay in Ephesus until Pentecost situates the letter within a specific chronological framework: written from Ephesus (Paul spent approximately 2-3 years there, Acts 19:1-20:1) before the spring sailing season. Pentecost (the Jewish feast of weeks, 50 days after Passover) fell in late May/June — the opening of the Mediterranean sailing season. Paul's timing is calculated around Jewish-Roman calendar conventions still used for seasonal travel planning even by Gentile-mission apostles.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The 'wide door for effective work' opened at Ephesus refers to the remarkable success of the Ephesian mission — Acts 19 describes spectacular conversions, exorcisms, and the book-burning that followed (Acts 19:11-20). The 'many adversaries' (<em>antikeimenos polloi</em>) were real: Ephesus had the Artemis cult, a significant silversmith trade dependent on the cult (Acts 19:23-41), Jewish magical practitioners, and possibly hostile synagogue authorities (Acts 19:8-9). The open door and opposition are not contradictory but characteristic of significant Christological advance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Timothy's expected visit to Corinth (cf. 4:17: 'I sent Timothy') reflects the network of apostolic emissaries through whom Paul maintained pastoral oversight across multiple communities simultaneously. Timothy is described as doing 'the work of the Lord' — apostolic missionary work — and deserves the community's respect and welcome. The concern that he be 'without fear' (<em>ina aphobōs genētai</em>) suggests that Corinth could be an intimidating community for emissaries — the Corinthians' factional tensions and intellectual sophistication required courage to navigate.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The instruction 'let no one despise him' (<em>mē tis oun auton exouthenēsē</em>) reflects the honor-shame dynamics of the Corinthian community. The Corinthians prized social status and rhetorical ability (ch. 1-2); Timothy was apparently young (1 Tim 4:12: 'let no one despise your youth') and possibly less rhetorically impressive than Apollos or Paul himself. The 'sending him on in peace' (<em>propempsate auton en eirēnē</em>) parallels the <em>propempthō</em> language of v. 6 — the community was responsible for properly honoring and equipping the apostle's representative.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Apollos's reluctance to visit Corinth 'at this time' is significant given the Apollos-party division of ch. 1:12. The phrase 'when he has opportunity' (<em>hotan eukarisē</em>) — if Paul's translation — suggests Apollos was independently deciding his travel schedule, not subject to Paul's direction. This reflects the reality that Apollos was an independent teacher and missionary (Acts 18:24-28), not Paul's subordinate. Paul's diplomatic handling of the Apollos situation — affirming him (3:5-6) while not over-explaining his absence — navigates the Corinthian factional politics carefully.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The four imperatives in v. 13 ('be watchful, stand firm in the faith, act like men, be strong') reflect standard ancient military and civic exhortation language. The Greek ideal of <em>andreia</em> (manliness/courage) was the cardinal virtue of the soldier and citizen; Paul's 'be men of courage' (<em>andrizesthe</em>) deploys this cultural value for Christian perseverance. The watchfulness language (<em>grēgoreite</em>) echoes eschatological vigilance (Mark 13:34-37; 1 Thess 5:6) — the community is on guard duty until the Lord's return.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Let all that you do be done in love' (<em>panta hymōn en agapē ginesthō</em>) is the summary principle that concludes the letter's specific instructions. After the extended treatment of love as the criterion for all gifts in ch. 13, and the practical applications throughout the letter, this summary integrates the entire practical argument. The Corinthians' characteristic failure was doing legitimate things (praying, prophesying, gathering, eating, exercising gifts) in self-promotional, honor-competitive, community-fracturing ways — without love as the operative mode.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Stephanas and his household as the 'firstfruits of Achaia' (<em>aparchē tēs Achaias</em>) — using the same firstfruits vocabulary as the resurrection argument of ch. 15:20 — were among the first Corinthian converts. The Stephanas household's 'appointed themselves for service to the saints' (<em>eis diakonion tois hagiois etaxan heautous</em>) describes a voluntary self-assignment to servant leadership within the community. This is one of the earliest references to self-organized community leadership in the Pauline churches, preceding formal episcopal structures.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The instruction to 'be subject to such people' (<em>hypotassēsthe tois toioutois</em>) and to every fellow worker and laborer provides a principle for community governance: the basis for authority is service and labor, not social status or rhetorical achievement. This inverts the Corinthian honor hierarchy (where status determined authority) and grounds leadership legitimacy in practical community service — a distinctively Christian reformulation of civic authority structures.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The visit of Stephanas, Fortunatus, and Achaicus to Paul in Ephesus was the occasion for oral news from Corinth that Paul responds to alongside the written letter. Their names are Roman-style: Stephanas (Greek) and Fortunatus/Achaicus (Latin — 'lucky' and 'from Achaia' respectively) reflect the mixed Greek-Roman naming conventions of the Corinthian colony. Their visit 'supplied what was lacking' in the Corinthians' contact with Paul — a reminder that this letter is a response to real people with specific concerns, not an abstract theological treatise.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'They refreshed my spirit and yours' (<em>anepausan gar to emon pneuma kai to hymon</em>) describes the mutual encouragement of apostolic visits in both directions: the community refreshes the apostle and the apostle refreshes the community. The honor-recognition requested ('give recognition to such people') follows the ancient pattern of communal recognition for patrons and benefactors (<em>euergetes</em>) — but here applied to servant-leaders rather than high-status patrons. Paul subverts the honorific system by directing its recognition toward those who serve.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The greetings from 'the churches of Asia' and specifically from Aquila and Priscilla with 'the church in their house' reflect the house-church structure of early Christianity. Aquila and Priscilla appear in three cities (Rome, Corinth, Ephesus) as hosts of house-church gatherings (Rom 16:5: 'the church in their house'; cf. Acts 18:2, 18, 26), suggesting a mobile, commercially-active couple whose home was consistently a center of Christian community. The Ephesian house-church sends greetings to the Corinthian house-church network — the horizontal connections of the Pauline mission.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The 'holy kiss' (<em>philēma hagion</em>) was the concrete social practice of Christian community greeting, attested across multiple Pauline letters (Rom 16:16; 2 Cor 13:12; 1 Thess 5:26) and in 1 Pet 5:14. The kiss was a normal Greco-Roman greeting between social equals and family members; the 'holy' qualifier marks it as a ritualized community greeting that enacted kinship across social boundaries. Kissing a social inferior would have been unusual in Roman culture; the holy kiss normalized egalitarian physical affection within the church family.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The autograph greeting in Paul's own hand ('the greeting is in my own hand, Paul') was a standard authenticating device in ancient letters where the main body was written by a secretary (<em>amanuensis</em>). Paul regularly dictated his letters (Rom 16:22: Tertius identifies himself as the scribe) and added a closing signature as verification. This authenticating convention protected against forgeries — an ongoing problem in the early church (2 Thess 2:2; 3:17). The shift to Paul's own hand marked the letter's genuine apostolic origin.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Let him be accursed' (<em>anathema</em>) and 'Maranatha' (<em>marana tha</em>): the juxtaposition is startling. The accursed formula is the opposite of blessing — the devotion to destruction of the one who does not love the Lord. 'Maranatha' is the only Aramaic phrase preserved in Paul's Greek letters (cf. Rev 22:20: 'Come, Lord Jesus') — an indication that this was a liturgical formula so established in early Christian worship that it crossed linguistic boundaries unchanged. 'Our Lord, come' (<em>maran atha</em>, Aramaic) was the primitive Christian prayer at the eucharistic gathering, preserved even in the Greek-speaking communities as an ancient and venerated expression.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'The grace of the Lord Jesus be with you' — the closing grace-benediction is the standard Pauline letter-closing, appearing in all thirteen letters attributed to Paul. The form is parallel to the ancient epistolary closing (<em>errhōso</em>, farewell; or <em>hygiainein</em>, be in good health) but transformed: the source of the closing wish is not generic goodwill but the specific grace of the Lord Jesus. The closing integrates the entire letter's concerns — the grace that was given to Paul (15:10), that the Corinthians received (1:4), and that shapes all ethical life — into the final apostolic word.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'My love be with you all in Christ Jesus' — the personal closing in which Paul declares his own love for the fractured, problematic, beloved Corinthian community. After an entire letter addressing their divisions, lawsuits, sexual misconduct, eucharistic disorder, gift competition, and resurrection denial, the closing word is love (<em>hē agapē mou</em>, my love). The 'in Christ Jesus' grounds the love in the same location as all the community's identity: the community's existence 'in Christ' is both the reason Paul loves them and the sphere within which that love is expressed and received. The letter that began with thanksgiving (1:4) ends with love (16:24).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1corinthians')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH15)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH16)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1corinthians', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'1 Corinthians mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
